      <hedline>
        <hl1>Religion and Public Life</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>William S Weiss letter on Aug 31 editorial opposes more religion in public life</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It is not ''fine to call for more religion in American public life'' (editorial, Aug. 31).</p>
        <p>Successive Supreme Courts have interpreted the First Amendment as keeping most religious expression out of public life. Although Americans have shown tolerance, majorities in many countries have used government and public life to crush minorities who did not share their religious beliefs, race or ethnic background.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It is not ''fine to call for more religion in American public life'' (editorial, Aug. 31).</p>
        <p>Successive Supreme Courts have interpreted the First Amendment as keeping most religious expression out of public life. Although Americans have shown tolerance, majorities in many countries have used government and public life to crush minorities who did not share their religious beliefs, race or ethnic background.</p>
        <p>Ours is the most religiously tolerant nation on earth, with more churches, mosques, synagogues and temples than any other country. Americans have ample opportunity for religious expression. There's no need to encourage it in public life.</p>
        <p>WILLIAM S. WEISS  Summit, N.J., Aug. 31, 2000</p>
      </block>
